<span class="displaytext"><b>(candidate last) campaign responds to sen. (candidate last) attacks</b> <p>senator (candidate last) attacked senator (candidate last) today for not standing up to the oil industry. really? senator (candidate last) is the only candidate that voted for the bush-cheney energy bill and took more money from oil company executives than any other candidate last month: </p><p><b>(candidate last) spokesman phil singer said: "sen. (candidate last) might say he doesn't take contributions from oil companies, but he took more money last month from oil company executives than any other candidate. he might say he'll stand up to the oil companies but he's the only candidate who voted for the bush-cheney energy bill that was written by energy lobbyists and has been called the best energy bill corporations could buy." </b></p><p>"with gas prices this high, talk is cheap. the american people need solutions." </p><p>fact check: sen. (candidate last) rakes in oil money, supported energy bill </p><p>sen. (candidate last) accepted more money from oil execs last month than any other candidate </p><p>sen. (candidate last) accepted more money from oil company executives last month than any other candidate, while he ran an ad saying he didn't take money from oil companies. "sen. (candidate full) continued accepting donations from oil company executives and employees last month even as he aired ads in which he stated he took no oil company money, his campaign finance reports show. (candidate last) has taken at least $263,000 from oil company executives, family members and employees since entering the presidential race last year, including $46,000 last month. at least $140,000 has come in chunks of between $1,000 and $2,300, the maximum permitted under federal law." (candidate last)'s [la times, 4/24/08] sen. (candidate last) voted for the bush/cheney 2005 energy bill </p><p>sen. (candidate last) voted for the 2005 energy bill, hillary opposed: [h.r. 6, vote #213, 0